<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-18</title>

<p>This run found three papers that each argue, in different ways, that the next leap in embodied and multimodal AI comes from <b>looping</b> rather than scaling: Guava shows that a well-designed harness can transfer embodied manipulation into a 4B model with fewer than 2K trajectories; Kairos treats long-horizon world modeling as a deployment-first architecture problem, not a data problem; and OmniAgent reframes long-video understanding as a query-driven POMDP in which perception itself is a reasoning action. All three have concrete artifacts to inspect—two with public code, one with a detailed project page—so the report grounds each claim in either traced implementation, a runnable probe, or an explicit blocker.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> OmniAgent (2606.19341) is the clearest seed for a research thread. Its released code implements the TAURA entropy-rescaled advantage exactly as described, and the OTA loop's strict media-purging makes the "active perception as reasoning" claim concrete. A 7B agent beating a 10× larger passive model while using 73% fewer frames is the kind of result that is worth understanding from the code up.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Harnessing embodied agents</h1>

<p>The dominant story in robot learning has been end-to-end vision-language-action models trained on hundreds of thousands of real trajectories. The papers in this theme ask whether a smaller open model, wrapped in the right harness, can be enough. Guava is the strongest example; the shortlist contains related efforts in agentic environments and memory-driven evolution.</p>

