<h2>Guava: An Effective and Universal Harness for Embodied Manipulation</h2>

<p>Haowen Liu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.18363">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.18363">PDF</a> · <a href="https://guava-harness.github.io">Project page</a></p>

<p>Guava's central claim is that <b>harness design</b>—not model size—can unlock embodied manipulation. The authors identify three ingredients: iterative ReAct-style perception-reasoning-action loops, semantic action abstractions (grasp, align, move, release), and multimodal observations that combine an RGB view with a compact symbolic state. They then distill the resulting behavior into a 4B Qwen3.5-4B model using only 1,934 trajectories collected in simulation, and report zero-shot real-world Franka deployment.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:guava:overview]]</p>

<p>The paper's ablations make the design argument quantitative. On six long-horizon Robosuite tasks, moving from a one-shot harness to a closed-loop ReAct harness, from a low-level numeric action space to semantic tools, and from text-only to multimodal observations each gives large gains. The most striking result is that Guava-Agent-4B reaches an overall 75.6% success rate, above GPT-5.4 (70.2%) and a concurrent CaP-Agent0 baseline (62.7%). RL post-training is applied only to the two hardest long-horizon tasks and raises shell-game performance from 6.7% to 60.0%.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:guava:react-ablation]]</p>

<p>Because the project page lists code as "coming soon," I built a minimal pure-Python probe of the harness idea. The probe places a red cube in a basket using semantic tools and a hand-written ReAct policy; it can recover from a simulated grasp failure. Three ablations isolate the ingredients:</p>

<pre lang="text" caption="Guava probe: 20-trial Monte Carlo over stochastic grasp failures"><code>ReAct + semantic + multimodal       success 20/20  avg_steps 6.0
One-shot open-loop plan             success 12/20  avg_steps 4.0
Low-level numeric moves             success  0/20  avg_steps 20.0
Text-only observations              success  0/20  avg_steps 6.0</code></pre>

<p>The toy environment confirms that each ingredient is load-bearing: iteration handles failure, semantic tools spare the planner from geometry, and the visual channel disambiguates otherwise identical objects. What the probe cannot verify is the headline real-world transfer, the exact data-engine curation, or the GRPO recipe, because none of those artifacts are public yet. The nearest open comparator with code is CaP-X/CaP-Agent0; Guava differentiates itself by distilling the harness into a compact model rather than treating the harness as a test-time-only scaffold.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:guava:reasoning-trace]]</p>

<hr/>

<h1>World models as deployable infrastructure</h1>

<p>Kairos is the most ambitious world-model stack in the pool: it wants to learn, maintain, and run worlds for physical AI. The shortlist contains two other structural contributions—3D-consistent multi-view generation and a large egocentric game dataset—that share the same conviction: world models must become operational substrates, not just video generators.</p>

