<h2>Kairos: A Native World Model Stack for Physical AI</h2>

<p>Kairos Team (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.16533">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.16533">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/kairos-agi/kairos-sensenova">Code</a></p>

<p>Kairos argues that world models must be built as operational infrastructure from the start: they need a native cross-embodiment curriculum, a unified understanding-generation-prediction architecture, and deployment-aware co-design. The most concrete part of this vision is the <b>Hybrid Linear Temporal Attention</b> inside the DiT backbone. Local dynamics are handled by sliding-window attention (SWA), mid-range dependencies by dilated sliding-window attention (DSWA), and persistent global memory by Gated Linear Attention (GLA).</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:kairos:architecture]]</p>

<p>The GLA update is a delta rule with a forget gate. At each step the model retrieves the old value associated with the current key, writes a corrected value, and decays the state matrix:</p>

<latex>
\mathbf{v}_t^{\text{old}} = \mathbf{S}_{t-1} \mathbf{k}_t, \quad
\mathbf{v}_t^{\text{new}} = \beta_t \mathbf{v}_t + (1 - \beta_t) \mathbf{v}_t^{\text{old}},
</latex>

<latex>
\mathbf{S}_t = \alpha_t \mathbf{S}_{t-1} - \mathbf{v}_t^{\text{old}} \mathbf{k}_t^{\top} + \mathbf{v}_t^{\text{new}} \mathbf{k}_t^{\top}
= \alpha_t \mathbf{S}_{t-1} + \beta_t (\mathbf{v}_t - \mathbf{v}_t^{\text{old}}) \mathbf{k}_t^{\top}.
</latex>

<p>The theory proves that a purely local window cannot recover supra-window state (Theorem 1), and that a contractive global memory bounds long-horizon excess risk by</p>

<latex>
\mathcal{R}_t(\hat{\mu}_t) - \mathcal{R}_t^{\star} \le \left( L\varepsilon + \frac{L_G \bar{\xi}}{1 - \rho} \right)^2.
</latex>

<p>Tracing the official repo confirms the factorization is hard-coded. <code>KairosDiT</code> schedules a <code>GatedDeltaNet</code> GLA block every fourth layer; the others are <code>SelfAttention</code> with frame-scaled windows and dilation. The 4B config uses 32 layers, dim 2560, 20 heads, and <code>dilated_lengths = [1, 1, 4, 1]</code>:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="From kairos/modules/dits/kairos_dit.py"><code>use_linear_attns = [(i + 1) % 4 == 0 for i in range(num_layers)]
...
DiTBlock(..., use_linear_attn=(i + 1) % 4 == 0,
         dilated_length=dilated_lengths[i % 4], ...)</code></pre>

<p>The repo is inference-oriented, so the data curriculum and training code are paper-only. But the deployment co-design is fully present: TeaCache timestep skipping, DMD distillation, sequence/tensor parallelism, SageAttention/FlashAttention kernels, tiled VAE, chunked FFN, and VRAM offloading are all wired into the same pipeline. A toy NumPy probe confirms the necessity claim: on a cue-recovery task where only the first token carries class information, a pure sliding-window baseline stays near chance while GLA and Hybrid retain near-perfect accuracy across horizons up to 120 steps.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:kairos:probe-result]]</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:kairos:data-curriculum]]</p>

