<h2>OmniAgent: Native Active Perception as Reasoning</h2>

<p>Zhenghao Xing et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.19341">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2606.19341">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/harryhsing/OmniAgent">Code</a></p>

<p>OmniAgent attacks the "watch-it-all" cost of long-video models by treating video understanding as a POMDP. The agent maintains a persistent textual memory and a transient raw-media percept. At each turn it emits an Observation–Thought–Action triplet; the environment executes the action, returns a new raw percept, and <b>purges</b> the old one. The context cost is meant to scale with the reasoning trace, not the video duration.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:omniagent:ota-framework]]</p>

<p>The action grammar is exactly the paper's four actions: <code>get_frames</code>, <code>get_audio</code>, <code>get_clip</code>, and <code>answer</code>. The training pipeline has two stages. Agentic SFT bootstraps the OTA loop from 58K best-of-N trajectories with outcome verification and a GPT-4o rationality audit. Agentic RL then refines the policy with TAURA (Turn-aware Adaptive Uncertainty Rescaled Advantage), which addresses the advantage homogenization problem in multi-turn GRPO.</p>

<p>Vanilla GRPO broadcasts a single trajectory-level advantage to every token. TAURA rescales it by the per-turn mean token entropy:</p>

<latex>
\hat{A}_{i,k} = A_i \cdot \frac{H_{i,k}}{\frac{1}{N_{\mathcal{G}}} \sum_{j=1}^{G} \sum_{m=1}^{K_j} H_{j,m}}.
</latex>

<p>Tracing the released code shows that TAURA is implemented under the flag <code>entropy_weight=true</code>. In <code>verl/trainer/ppo/core_algos.py</code>, <code>get_entropy_weights</code> computes the per-turn mean entropy and normalizes by the query-group mean, then <code>ray_trainer.py</code> multiplies the GRPO advantage by that weight. The vanilla GRPO baseline is the same launch script with <code>entropy_weight=false</code>. The match to Equation 4 is exact; only the internal name differs.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:omniagent:accuracy-vs-frames]]</p>

<p>A small synthetic probe reproduces the intended asymmetry. When one turn per trajectory is given elevated entropy to mimic a "discovery" fork, TAURA boosts the high-entropy turn magnitude by about 1.3× while down-weighting low-entropy routine turns. The full 7B model was not run locally because it needs a large GPU, vLLM, and the released checkpoints; the probe isolates the credit-assignment mechanism.</p>

<p>The empirical headline is that OmniAgent-7B reaches 50.5% on LVBench, above Qwen2.5-VL-72B (47.3%) while sampling ~73% fewer frames (203 vs. 768). Test-time scaling is also positive: accuracy on VideoMME-Long rises from 53.4% to 59.6% as the turn budget grows, but the average number of executed turns saturates around 11.7 even when the cap is 52. The agent learns to stop once it has enough evidence rather than burning budget.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:omniagent:test-time-scaling]]</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting observations</h1>

<p>Two patterns cut across the deep threads.</p>

<p><b>Loops, not just scale.</b> Guava, Kairos, and OmniAgent all replace a single forward pass with an explicit loop: ReAct tool use, recurrent GLA memory, and the OTA perception cycle. In each case the loop is treated as a first-class design decision, not as a sampling trick on top of a frozen model.</p>

<p><b>Deployment as a method constraint.</b> Kairos co-designs attention, kernels, and memory so the model can run on a robot; Guava distills into a 4B model so the harness is cheap enough to call repeatedly; OmniAgent caps context cost by discarding raw media each turn. Efficiency is not an afterthought—it shapes what the method is.</p>

<p><b>What remains uncertain.</b> For Guava, the absence of training code and task definitions means the real-world transfer claim is plausible but unverified. For Kairos, the Cross-Embodiment Data Curriculum is described in detail but not present in the public repo, so the pre-training story cannot be independently inspected. For OmniAgent, the code matches the paper, but the strongest result depends on checkpoints and compute that are out of reach here. The loop-level insights, however, are portable.</p>
